														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3648592">
									

<p>I feel similarly to <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3122708); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3122708&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1512792960" alt="The Great Hippo" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3122708)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3122708); return false;">The Great Hippo</a></span>. I didn't find it depressing, considering my own work (and there's a lot of me in that - let's face it, we all invent our own meat puppets for torture and we're always somewhat related. Right? &#8230;Right?) but I did find it interesting enough to keep reading, for sure. I wanted to know what happened, and to read something that resonated with me personally. I felt like you captured dissociation in your work without being too direct about it. That's what I took from it, anyway.</p>
<p>I also agree if you weren't such a good writer, this could have easily gone down in flames. But you're a good, and established writer, so you have the ability to express yourself clearly in a somewhat unusual, more blog-like, format.</p>

							</div>

								
