					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tomatointhemirror" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2765984); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2765984&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205763" alt="TomatointheMirror" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2765984)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tomatointhemirror" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2765984); return false;" >TomatointheMirror</a></span> <span class="odate time_1513088107 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 Dec 2017 14:15</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3650585">
									

<p>This is just too self-indulgent and meta for me.</p>
<p>The main difference between this and other tales in the series is that the others were presented as in-universe stories (discounting the end of the previous entry) but this one is presented as a story about the author. Which is you. You wrote a tale about yourself and put it in the tale series and I don't understand why. Sure, it's breaking conventions, but it's breaking a unwritten rule that I feel has a very good reason for existing: Authors should not write stories where they are the main character. (Unless it's an autobiography or something along those lines, but we don't have those here. Either that or I'm missing out on a lot of content.)</p>

							</div>

								
							<div class="changes">
					Last edited on <span class="odate time_1513097566 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 Dec 2017 16:52</span>
