															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2005044&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205763" alt="Decibelles" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2005044)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;" >Decibelles</a></span> <span class="odate time_1513102837 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 Dec 2017 18:20</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3650710">
									

<p>It’s fine if you don’t like it, but if you don’t see how this story fits into the series, then you haven’t been paying attention to the metaphors throughout and the relationship between author and story, not actually figured out what the series is ultimatey about. I won’t comment on the specifics but spoiler for those lads who do declassified stuff and analysis: it’s a tale series about the author.</p>
<p>This tale is just as relevant as every othet tale in the series; the only difference was that I got more literal here. Also; all rules for writing are made to be broken. The only actual firm rule you have to follow is that you have to be some form of entertaining or engaging. To be boring or a slog is the worst thing writing can do.</p>
<p>I mean&#8230; shit, <a href="https://www.barnesandnoble.com/blog/5-times-a-bestselling-author-put-themselves-in-the-book-and-nailed-it/">I’m not even the first one to think of writing a story set in fiction where the ligeral authors are part of it</a>. I’ve been in this tale series from the get-go, I’m just making the terms clear.</p>

							</div>

								
					
